properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Areas of brief, intense snowfall are expected early this morning from frontal snow squalls. A cold front moving over the area from Georgian Bay will continue to result in sudden low visibilities and a quick accumulation of snow early this morning. Total snowfall amounts near 10 cm are possible, especially in the Parry Sound area and inland towards Bracebridge. After the cold front winds will become northwesterly and isolated lake effect snow squalls will develop to the southeast of Georgian Bay. Some of the snow squalls may give snowfall accumulations near 15 centimetres by Wednesday evening. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Maximum gusts: Southwesterly between 100 and 130 km/h. Locations: southern half of the Burin Peninsula, most of the Avalon Peninsula. Time span: midnight Wednesday night to Thursday morning. Remarks: After the southwesterlies diminish Thursday morning, winds will shift to northwesterly. Over the northern Avalon Peninsula winds will likely gust between 80 and 100 km/h Thursday afternoon. Additionally, large waves and pounding surf are expected in Placentia and St. Mary's Bays over Wednesday night. Water levels may be higher than normal during that time giving the potential for minor coastal flooding, especially near high tide. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may cause downed trees or toss loose objects. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and blowing snow expected late Wednesday and Thursday. Total Snowfall: 15 to 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: Generally northwesterly near 80 km/h. Northwesterly gusts near 100 km/h are expected in the Port aux Basques area overnight Wednesday night. Gusts between 100 and 120 km/h will develop along the northeast coast on Thursday morning. Locations: Port aux Basques to Gros Morne, Central and Northeastern Newfoundland. Time span: Wednesday afternoon or evening to Thursday evening. Remarks: Snow at times heavy will combine with strong winds to reduce visibility in blowing snow Wednesday night and Thursday. Conditions will gradually improve by Thursday evening as winds and snow diminish. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, blowing snow, and strong winds for Thursday. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm (5 to 10 cm Wednesday night, 5 cm Thursday) Maximum wind gusts: Easterly 60 to 80 km/h (Wednesday night), north to northwesterly 80 to 120 km/h (Thursday). Locations: Eastern and Northeastern Newfoundland. Time span: late Wednesday afternoon to Thursday evening. Remarks: A low pressure system will cross eastern Newfoundland on Wednesday night into Thursday morning. Snow will begin late Wednesday afternoon before changing to rain or drizzle near midnight on Wednesday night. Rain will change back to snow before morning on Thursday causing conditions to deteriorate throughout the day. Strong north to northwesterly winds will develop Thursday morning, combining with fresh snow to produce poor visibility in blowing snow. Wind warnings are likely, blowing snow advisories are possible. Conditions will improve Thursday evening as the winds and snow diminish. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant winter storm expected Saturday. A low pressure system will impact southern Ontario this weekend. Rain, freezing rain, and snow are all possible with this system. Significant rainfall amounts are expected for areas north of Lake Erie and Lake Ontario. Freezing rain is expected to affect most areas east of Lake Huron and eastern Ontario. Significant ice accretion or build up is possible. Snow will affect areas east of Georgian Bay with significant snowfall amounts. Travel is expected to be impacted. There is still uncertainty as to which areas will be the most impacted with this system. The Ontario Storm Prediction Centre will be closely monitoring the situation. Warnings may be issued as the event draws nearer. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:

Wind chill values near -45 are expected to develop overnight into tomorrow morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Maximum wind gusts: northeasterly near 70 km/h Wednesday evening, northwesterly near 70 km/h Wednesday night and Thursday morning. Total Snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Location: Inland over the Burgeo highway. Time span: Wednesday afternoon to early Thursday morning. Remarks: Fresh snow and moderate winds will combine to cause poor visibility in blowing snow, especially inland along the Burgeo highway. Conditions along the coast should be less severe. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Pacific frontal system will continue to cross southern B.C. tonight bringing heavy snowfall to Highway 3 between Paulson Summit and Kootenay Pass. Storm totals from this two-day event have reached 38 cm (as of 4pm MST) and a further 10-20 cm is expected before precipitation eases Wednesday afternoon. ### Rapidly accumulating snow and drifting snow will make travel very difficult. Poor weather conditions are likely to contribute to long-lasting transportation delays. Expect road closures as avalanches are possible. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Areas of brief, intense snowfall are expected early this morning from frontal snow squalls. A cold front moving over the area from Georgian Bay will continue to result in sudden low visibilities and a quick accumulation of snow early this morning. Total snowfall amounts near 10 cm are possible, especially south of Parry Sound and inland towards Bracebridge. After the cold front winds will become northwesterly and isolated lake effect snow squalls will develop to the southeast of Georgian Bay. Some of the snow squalls may give snowfall accumulations near 15 centimetres by Wednesday evening. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
